  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Through FY2026 to date, federal contract obligations in Florida total $18.5B, with 127,871 awards and an average award size of $145K; current-year totals are partial. Obligations fell 43.1% year over year. Annual obligations peaked at $32.5B in FY25 and then declined to $18.5B in FY26. The Department of Defense accounts for the largest share of FY2026 to date obligations at $12.1B, followed by the Department of Veterans Affairs at $2.5B and the General Services Administration at $1.4B. Leading vendors by dollars include LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION with $2.4B and a second listing for LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION at $2.1B, LOYAL SOURCE GOVERNMENT SERVICES LLC at $1.8B, and NORTHROP GRUMMAN SYSTEMS CORPORATION at $885M. Industry concentrations are in Guided Missile and Space Vehicle Manufacturing at $4.3B, Offices of Physicians at $1.8B, and Engineering Services at $1.4B. The FY2026-to-date profile shows a smaller total than prior fiscal years and a concentration of obligations in defense, aerospace, medical offices, and engineering services.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "What drove the year-over-year decline in obligations?",
        "body": "Obligations fell 43.1% year over year, with FY26-to-date totals at $18.5B versus $32.5B in FY25. The drop follows a multi-year rise from $25.7B in FY21 to $32.5B in FY25, then a sharp reduction to $18.5B in FY26. This shift reduced the aggregate dollars flowing through the 127,871 awards recorded in FY26 to date."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which agencies and vendors dominate Florida federal contracting?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense leads FY2026-to-date obligations with $12.1B, followed by the Department of Veterans Affairs at $2.5B and the General Services Administration at $1.4B. Top vendors by dollars include LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION at $2.4B and again at $2.1B, LOYAL SOURCE GOVERNMENT SERVICES LLC at $1.8B, and NORTHROP GRUMMAN SYSTEMS CORPORATION at $885M. Industry concentration is strongest in Guided Missile and Space Vehicle Manufacturing at $4.3B and Offices of Physicians at $1.8B."
      }
    ]
  },
